	<h2>The Economic Function of the Dollar Slice</h2>
	<p>The "dollar slice" (now frequently $1.50 or $2.00 due to inflation) operates as the foundational late-night and low-budget meal in New York City. These establishments prioritize volume over artisanal quality, providing rapid caloric intake at minimum cost.</p>
	
	<h3>Quality Control</h3>
	<p>Never judge a dollar slice establishment by its ambiance. The primary metric for quality is turnover rate. A busy shop produces fresh pies continuously. A quiet shop serves slices that have degraded under heat lamps for hours. Always select the slice shop with a line.</p>

	<h2>Key Establishments</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>2 Bros Pizza:</strong> The corporate standard of the dollar slice. Locations are ubiquitous across Manhattan. Quality is consistent and turnover is universally high.</li>
		<li><strong>Percy's Pizza:</strong> Located in Greenwich Village. It maintains the strict $1 price point and offers a slightly thinner, crispier crust than competitors.</li>
		<li><strong>St. Marks Pizza:</strong> Operates at a slightly higher price point ($3-$4) but functions as the central hub for late-night dining in the East Village.</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Consumption Protocol</h3>
	<p>Dollar slice pizza must be folded lengthwise before consumption to maintain structural integrity. Do not request custom toppings. Do not use a fork and knife. Pay in cash to expedite the transaction.</p>
</InternWiki>
